**Lua script correctness argument:**  
The script atomically prunes expired entries via `ZREMRANGEBYSCORE`, counts remaining entries with `ZCARD`, and conditionally adds a new timestamp—all in a single Redis evaluation, ensuring two concurrent `allow()` calls cannot both succeed when only one slot remains. Memory efficiency is achieved because pruning happens before counting in every call, so stale entries are removed in the same atomic pass without storing them indefinitely. Clock skew resilience comes from using Redis's `TIME` command as the authoritative time source, guaranteeing all application servers operate from the same clock. Finally, the script returns `allowed`, `remaining`, and `reset_at` in one round-trip, satisfying the requirement for accurate queries without additional calls.

